<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1818,2022]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1436,151,500]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,317,1853,1878]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">DIAGNOSIS:</emphasis>
Adults often bright green in life (
<figureCitation box="[715,799,1854,1878]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–91" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1156,1179]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,159,1143]" captionTargetId="figure-55@63.[151,1436,159,1168]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 90–91. Alloperla. 90: Habitus (live), Alloperla rostellata, Tariakhtain Stream (SRP2005070902).; 91: Comparative distribution map." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 90</figureCitation>
) and often lack the dark pigmentation characteristic of many other chloroperlids. All 
<taxonomicName box="[506,704,1890,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[506,612,1890,1914]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Alloperla</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
known from 
<collectingCountry box="[869,980,1890,1914]" name="Mongolia" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
, except 
<taxonomicName authority="Zapekina-Dulkeit, 1970" authorityName="Zapekina-Dulkeit" authorityYear="1970" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis box="[1080,1220,1890,1914]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">A. deminuta</emphasis>
Zapekina-Dulkeit, 1970
</taxonomicName>
, have a medial, dark, abdominal stripe (
<figureCitation box="[683,768,1926,1950]" captionStart="FIGURES 96–99" captionStartId="64.[151,264,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,193,920]" captionTargetId="figure-69@64.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 96–99. Alloperla joosti. 96: Habitus (preserved); 97: Male terminalia; 98: Female terminalia, ventral; 99: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 96</figureCitation>
) which is thinner in comparison to other 
<taxonomicName box="[1261,1432,1926,1950]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chloroperlidae</taxonomicName>
, particularly 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1934" box="[288,417,1962,1986]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Haploperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[288,417,1962,1986]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Haploperla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. One species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1925" box="[581,703,1962,1986]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediata">
<emphasis box="[581,703,1962,1986]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">A. mediata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has a narrow medial stripe on the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1273,1372,1962,1986]" captionStart="FIGURES 100–103" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1085,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-73@64.[151,1436,1085,1854]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 100–103. Alloperla mediata. 100: Habitus (preserved); 101: Male terminalia.; 102: Female terminalia, ventral; 103: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 100</figureCitation>
). The male epiproct is at least slightly swollen at the base (
<figureCitation box="[753,852,1998,2022]" captionStart="FIGURES 100–103" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1085,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-73@64.[151,1436,1085,1854]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 100–103. Alloperla mediata. 100: Habitus (preserved); 101: Male terminalia.; 102: Female terminalia, ventral; 103: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
). Most species have ventral spines near the apex of the epiproct, with the exception of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zapekina-Dulkeit" authorityYear="1970" box="[552,688,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis box="[552,688,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. deminuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female subgenital plates are typically triangular (
<figureCitation box="[1268,1353,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 96–99" captionStartId="64.[151,264,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,193,920]" captionTargetId="figure-69@64.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 96–99. Alloperla joosti. 96: Habitus (preserved); 97: Male terminalia; 98: Female terminalia, ventral; 99: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 98</figureCitation>
), again with the exception of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zapekina-Dulkeit" authorityYear="1970" box="[398,534,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis box="[398,534,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. deminuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which has a small, subtriangular protrusion confined to the middle of the plate. Nymphs are concolorous (
<figureCitation box="[463,550,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 81–89" captionStartId="62.[151,263,1841,1864]" captionTargetBox="[166,1420,193,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-92@62.[166,1420,193,1821]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 81–89. Chloroperlidae genus key.81: Cerci of Alloperla sp., lateral; 82: Head and pronotum of Alloperla sp., dorsal; 83: Cerci of Suwallia teleckojensis, lateral; 84: Head and pronotum of Alaskaperla longidentata, dorsal; 85: Head and pronotum of Haploperla lepnevae., dorsal; 86: Head and pronotum of Suwallia teleckojensis, dorsal; 87: Abdomen of Alaskaperla longidentata, dorsal; 88: Thorax of Suwallia teleckojensis, dorsal; 89: Thorax of Alaskaperla longidentata, dorsal." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
) and characterized by many long intrasegmental hairs on the distal cercal segments.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
